-- "run drops stdout on panic" regression — a RAW `panic "…"` call site in
-- eval.mdk that does NOT go through runtimePanic (here: `lookupFrames [] name
-- = panic (...)`, hit because the interpreter has no dispatch-table entry for
-- `assertSnapshot`).  Representative of the ~20 similar internal-invariant call
-- sites (evalIndex/evalSlice/evalRange/applyClosure/collectPartials/pPutStr/…)
-- that fire when the interpreter meets a value shape it doesn't expect ("type
-- confusion" class) -- they all compile to the SAME native `panic` extern
-- call our fix covers, so this one call site stands in for the whole class.
-- See index_oob.mdk for the full writeup.
--
-- Was `exit 3` until eval.mdk grew a real `exit` binding (2026-07-14,
-- ioExternBindings) — `exit` no longer reaches this raw-panic path under
-- `run` (it now cleanly exits 3), so it switched to `flushStdout`.  Then
-- `flushStdout` got a real no-op interp binding (2026-07-15, issue #71) and
-- stopped raw-panicking too, so this fixture switched to `assertSnapshot`:
-- a forward-declared snapshot-testing primitive (TESTING-DESIGN.md §4.7) that
-- is unimplemented in ALL THREE engines and has zero stdlib callers, so it
-- won't grow a binding soon.  It is unbound under `run` and thus still hits
-- the same "unbound identifier" raw-panic call site.  Driven run-only (see
-- `check_one raw_panic_site run-only` in the gate).
main : <IO, Stdout> Unit
main =
  println "SENTINEL"
  assertSnapshot "a" "b"
